@NODE AM-1 "Introduction"
   AppMenu is a utility for Workbench. It runs only under Release 2 (V37) and
later versions of the Amiga operating system. It's a commodity that adds menu
items to the Workbench Tools menu. When a menu item is activated, AppMenu
starts up a program you chosed. You can free define the items and programs to
execute. All programs are started as separate, asynchronous processes. You can
also choose arguments for these programs through icons or file requester.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-2 "Installing and running"
   To install AppMenu simple copy it where you want it to have. You can start
it from Workbench or from Shell. Or just place it in the WBStartup drawer.
The following arguments in the line command or the tool types in the icon are
all optional.

   CX_PRIORITY=n
   CX_POPUP=NO|YES
   CX_POPKEY=hotkey

See Workbench handbook for this commodity tool types. Defaults are pririty 0,
popup 'YES' and popkey 'shift f3'.

   FROM=prefs

'prefs' is the preferences file (default "ENVARC:AppMenu/AppMenu.prefs"), where
AppMenu saves the items description. Each item contain a menu item text, a
command text and a arguments specification.

   PROGITEM=NO|YES

If you don't want 'AppMenu...' item in Tools menu choose NO. Default is YES.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-3 "The interface"
   AppMenu's window presents a list gadget with its scroller and a string field
below, a separate string field, a cycle gadget, two buttons and a bank of four
buttons. It have a menu too.
To open the window press the hothey, activate 'AppMenu...' item in Tools menu,
run AppMenu again or use the "Exchange" program. "Exchange" can be use for some
other things too (see its docs).

   The gadgets are:

        @{" New " link AM-3.3}  @{" Del " link AM-3.4}     @{"    Menu Items    " link AM-3.0}
                                @{"    Arg    " link AM-3.2}
        @{"              Command              " link AM-3.1}

        @{"  Save  " link AM-3.5} @{"  Use   " link AM-3.6} @{" Cancel " link AM-3.7} @{"  Quit  " link AM-3.8}


   The menu items are:

      Project                  Edit
        @{" Open...    " link AM-6.0}             @{" Last Saved      " link AM-6.2}
        @{" Save       " link AM-3.5}             @{" Restore         " link AM-6.3}
        @{" Save As... " link AM-6.1}              ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
        @{" Use        " link AM-3.6}             @{" Copy To Clip    " link AM-6.4}
         About...                @{" Paste From Clip " link AM-6.5}
         ~~~~~~~~~~               ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
        @{" Cancel     " link AM-3.7}             @{" Move Item Up    " link AM-6.6}
        @{" Quit       " link AM-3.8}             @{" Move Item Down  " link AM-6.6}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-3.0 "Menu Items"
This listview gadgets show the item list. To change a item just select it.
Now you can update the command text. Press Return or Tab key or change @{" Arg " link AM-3.2}
gadget to activate the string field below the listview gadget. Here you can
modify the item text and press Return to take the item back to the list.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-3.1 "Command"
Type the program name and its arguments you want to execute. Note that you must
specify the full path of the command when you start AppMenu from Workbench.

It's possible to type several files when you separate them with
<Ctrl LCommand J>. All programs will be started synchronous. It's made internal
through the DOS function System() so you can use it by Workbench's item
'Execute Command...' or in Shell too.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-3.2 "Arg"
Select if and from where you want arguments to a command. The possibilities are:

Requester   If you activate the item a file requester appears and you can
            choose a file name as an argument to the command. You can cancel
            the execution too.

Icons       The names of selected icons in Workbench (if any) will be
            arguments.

Icons/Req   Same as above. If no icon selected as 'Requester'.

None        Execute command without extra arguments.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-3.3 "New"
Add a new item to the list. Just type a command text, choose @{" Arg " link AM-3.2} and write
a menu item text. To quick add a program put its icon in the AppMenu window.
Its name will be the item text and its path with the name the command. The
number of items you can add is limited only by available memory, the system
(V37) however creates only 63 selectable menu items. To add a new item befor
an existing item in the list simple select this item first.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-3.4 "Del"
Remove the selected item from the list.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-3.5 "Save"
Save the item list to the preferences file. Further as @{" Use " link AM-3.6}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-3.6 "Use"
Close window, use current list to create item in Tools menu and execute
commands of the chosen items.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-3.7 "Cancel"
Undo all changes in the list since the window is open, close it and use the old
list. Note that window's Close gadget and Hide from "Exchange" have the equal
function.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-3.8 "Quit"
Quit AppMenu. Ctrl-C makes it too. If the changed items are not saved
a requester appears.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-6.0 "Open..."
Load new items from a selected file. If the changed items are not saved
a requester appears.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-6.1 "Save As..."
Save the item list to a selected preferences file.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-6.2 "Last Saved"
Load the at last saved items.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-6.3 "Restore"
Undo all changes in the list since the window is open.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-6.4 "Copy To Clip"
Copy the command text to clip. You can use it later in Shell with >RCommand V>.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-6.5 "Paste From Clip"
Add a new item to the list. Its command text will be taken from clip.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-6.6 "Move Item Up/Down"
Move the selected item in the list by one up or down.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AM-4 "The Program and its Author"
   Yes, yes..., localization should be done but the 2.1 update (in Germany)
isn't still obtainable.

